In response to the message sent  15 May 85 15:07:04 EDT from HEDRICK@RUTGERS.ARPA

Charles,

I would assume there is nothing inherently wrong with having a domain
and host of the same name. A query for RICE.EDU that lands at the
RICE.EDU name server would result in the A record for the RICE.EDU in
the answer section, while a query for x.RICE.EDU (for non-null x) would
result in NS and A records in the authoritative and additional sections
respectively. This would handle the case even if the host and name server
had different addresses. I would think this a valuable feature, since
today's hosts are probably going to evolve into tomorrow's domains.

Thus, the appropriate response for RICE.EDU when there is in fact no
host RICE.EDU should by this reasoning be an authoritative "no."

Here's one for you: How can a busybody find out about the set of name
servers for a particular domain without actually resolving something
in that domain? By the above reasoning, you can't find the set of RICE.EDU
servers by simply mumbling RICE.EDU to the NIC. You can try to resolve
some j. random host in RICE.EDU and capture the name servers as
they go by while the namesolver is chugging away or you can use the NS
value in the type field of the query. THus, RICE.EDU might be a whole
lot different depending on whether the A or NS types were used in the query.

Dave
